segments.text: Has there been, over the years, a substantial increase in students in the field of poultry husbandry?
And has there been a change in the background of the students?
By background, I would have to say, let me preface that by saying a geographical background.
Have they come from different areas of the world?
Well, of course, I inherited, when I took over the department, I inherited no records.
And so it's not going to be easy for me to answer that accurately.
But in terms of numbers of students,
there has distinctly been an increase in numbers of students, both undergraduate, but particularly at the graduate level.
We have, since about 1950, we have probably had more graduate students
in the poetry department at Texas A&M University than any other institution in the United States.
I don't think there's any challenge, even a beginning challenge there.
And so that the increase in students has majorly been at the graduate level.
Has this increase been primarily students from the United States or from abroad?
They've been both, both.
Yes, indeed, they've been both.
Now the undergraduate students, there's just been a smattering of foreign undergraduate students.
They mostly take their undergraduate degrees at home.
and then come here for graduate work.
So most of the foreign students have been taking courses at the graduate level.
I believe earlier you were telling me something about the reason why there has been this tremendous increase in interest in poultry production around the world.
And maybe you can elaborate on that now.
something about trying to get more protein into the diet.
Yes.
Well, most of the so-called developing nations, we have called them by different names in the last 15 years, but the common term now is developing nations.
Most of the developing nations have their protein source

in the first place they have been inadequate in the amount of protein they have had available for human consumption and then secondly the major portion of that protein has been from plant sources and most plant proteins other than soy
soybean meal or soy, almost all of the plant proteins are deficient in lysine, which is one of the required essential amino acids, required or essential amino acids.
It cannot be synthesized by man himself.
And another one is methionine, and it cannot be synthesized by man, so it has to be dietarily provided.

So, these two being low in most of the plant proteins that these people had available to them has meant that they have, in some cases, they have actually not had taken full advantage, not been able to take full advantage
are the amount of protein they had because of the limitations of these two particular amino acids.
See, they couldn't take it from the diet.
A human being can't take the diet, the protein from the diet, synthesize it into human protein.
by any more than the limiting, the amino acid that is the lowest, the acquired amino acid that's the lowest.
And so for that reason, they have had, I figured a few years ago when I was in Bangladesh, I figured at that time that actually they were throwing away
are actually using for energy 17% of the protein they consumed because they didn't have enough lysine.
And so since meat proteins or animal proteins are quite high, or animal foods are quite high in these two particular amino acids, these developing countries have been anxious
to improve their dietary balance by introducing some animal protein into their consumption now many of them what animal protein they get is fish
But there's a limit to how much fish is available.
In some countries that are not close to the sea, they can't even take advantage of fish as being one of their animal proteins.
And so as a result of it, they have looked to methods of producing animal protein and introducing it into their diet.
Since poultry is at the present time the most efficient of the common domestic animals, it is the most efficient converter of feed to food protein that we have.

And so as a result of it, they have looked to poultry as being a way of supplementing their human diet without robbing their feed supplies, which some of them are capable of being used for human food.
And so that has created a national, international interest in poultry.
in poultry as a supplier of animal protein for improving the diets of these developing nations.
In fact, I was contacted about two weeks ago by one of the men who had been called by the
administrator of Saudi Arabia.
And they, as you know, the last few years, most of those Mid-Eastern countries have all the money they want.
Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Iraq, etc.
They have, because of the increase in oil prices, they have all kinds of money.
But agriculture-wise, they are very deficient.
But they do have the money to buy from outside, if they can get it to buy.
But most of their people, their rulers, they do not want to depend upon continuous importation of their food.
They want to develop their own agriculture so that...
They can be self-sufficient, or at least more so in the future than they are at the present time.
And so they were looking into the possibility of recruiting a team of American scientists who could go over there and develop, establish a poultry industry in the country.
and set it up so that it could continue to operate after the scientists had finished their job.
And this is being done in New Orleans.
Last week at the World's Party Congress, I was contacted by the man who is in charge of the agricultural development for Iraq.
and about the possibility of availability for coming over for government consulting work in the attempt to develop a poultry industry for their country.
I hope it develops.
He'll find somebody to do it.
I don't know who it'll be, but he'll find it because money is nohe actually spent nine million dollars for equipment while he was in New Orleans in the exhibit area of the World's Congress last week.
Money's not a problem.
No, so money's not a problem, right.
Has the number of foreign students from developing countries in your graduate program had some influence on the makeup of the coursework and the requirements for a degree, let us say?
No, I don't believe so, because we have tended to have a pretty good balance.
This, of course, is maybe a prejudiced opinion, but we think we have a very good balance

both between courses and of the subject matter within a given course between the basic material, which will work anywhere in the world, and applied material, which can be used for application to the specific problems of producing and feeding and marketing poultry.
And as a result, it has not been necessary for us to do a great modification.
Well, I think earlier you indicated that many of the students which you produce are really kind of generalists rather than specialists.
And I was wondering if all of your students had been from highly developed countries, if you possibly would have developed more specialists and fewer generalists.
No, I think because of the trend we have been going through.
See, we have been, in the United States, our units of production have been getting bigger and fewer.
And most of the board of directors of an integrated operation want one man who knows
whether this special man, the manager of the processing plant, is doing a good job or not.
He also wants to know, wants somebody who can tell him or check for him whether this man that's running the feed mill is doing a good job.
And so for that reason, domestically, the last 15 years, there's been a much richer demand for these generalists and management and production people than there were before.
And now we're at that stage where I think we're going to start going back toward more specialization.
And the foreign countries, the developing countries particularly, they can't afford
a geneticist, a nutritionist, and a market technologist, and a physiologist in every one of their operations.
And so what they're trying to do is to get a little shallower training, but get all of these disciplines, a workable level of all of these disciplines in one man, one or two men, you see.
And so for that reason, I think that explains why there's been this number of students in this area, in this generalized area.
Okay.
Earlier you indicated that
that during your first teaching at A&M, you did some summer research with vitamin deficiencies, perhaps in rats.
Have you continued the work with vitamin deficiencies since then?
I mean, did you switch over to chickens, vitamin needs for chickens, later on when you came back?
Yes, yes indeed.
All of my work since I came back from away, while I was there and since I have come back, all of my work has been with poetry in one form or another.
I've done no work with other animals since then.
What would you say had been some of the more important research that you had done
since 1946?
Well, this gives me an opportunity to brag an awful lot.
I hope you won't consider it to be too much so, but it may sound that way.
That's what I'm trying to lay the foundation for.
Please don't
The others have worked along the same lines and so on.
And so much of the work has been done by graduate students and by other staff people and so on.
And for that reason, I will mention only those areas where I think we have made at least some original contribution to the area, that's all.

And I believe that one of these areas has been the development of the idea that for laying hens, we need to do, for optimum performance and for most economical cost of that performance, that so-called phase feeding is essential.
Now, we've always phase fed broilers.
In other words, we sometimes have a pre-starter, then a starter, and then a finisher diet.
But at least if we don't have a pre-starter, we have a starter and a finisher.
Now that's only eight weeks.
We market our broilers usually at eight weeks, plus or minus a few days.
And so this has been accepted.
But the tendency up until a few years ago, the tendency was to establish one ration for laying hens
and feed this same ration until the hens had finished their production period and were discarded.
Actually, in the winter months we need more energy to keep their body temperature up and in the summertime we need to reduce the energy because the body temperature is
The environmental temperature, they lose no heat to the environment, you see.
So that's what I mean by this phase feeding, just one element.
There's many elements of it.
But we need to change the ratio of protein to energy, for example, according to the season.
Wintertime, we have more energy, less protein.
In the summer, we'll have the same daily consumption.
But the ratio is what I'm talking about here.
Protein, perhaps, is needed in both seasons.
But the ratio of energy to protein is higher in the wintertime and lower in the summer.
And the same thing is true of calcium, the feed consumption.
Our data, we fed birds individually, and we find that in the summertime they may eat only 90 to 95 grams of feed.
Whereas in the wintertime, the feed consumption, the same diet, may go up to 115, 120 grams.
Well now, if you're only going to get 90 grams, and the bird's laying at the same rate and she's consuming 115 grams,

naturally there's got to be some changes not just in energy and protein but there's also got to be some changes in calcium because they've got to lay down shells around those eggs and there's got to be a change in vitamin level because you've got to get enough vitamin out of 90 grams
And over here, if you put enough in 90 grams and you put the same level in 115 grams, you're wasting a lot of it down there.
So in order for economy, we've simply got to go to this so-called phase feeding.
Now, another area where we entered about five years ago, we find that we can do more economical feeding if we control the feed intake.
That birds will tend, laying birds will tend to overconsume, consume more than they need to.
And gain a little extra body weight.
Well, the more body weight they gain, the more the maintenance requirement to maintain that body, see?
So if we can keep their body weight down a little bit, we actually make more, the cost of feed makes up about two-thirds of the total cost of producing eggs.
So we can do that.
We had a paper that was reported in New Orleans at the World Congress last week.
it attracted a lot of attention.
They took up the time for two papers to ask questions in this area.
There were some other papers from other countries in the same area.
So we think perhaps here is another area in which we have also made some contribution to this.
I hadn't had a chance to think about...
Could you stop the...

Another area in which we have worked fairly extensively here, and we should do it because we produce a tremendous amount of grain sorghum in this state, and so we have done a lot of feeding of grain sorghum to poultry, particularly layers.
Most of my research program has been with layers.

And so we have fed different varieties, different colors, that is yellow versus red, and the bird resistant, we've tested the bird resistant, the so-called bird resistant Milo, whether it actually reduces performance of layers and so on or not.
I don't know that you've seen it, but there was about two or three years ago, there was a book published on the production and utilization of grain sorghums.
And Dr. Tanksley at Animal Science and I were asked to write a chapter on the feeding of grain sorghums to swine, to poultry, and to swine, or to swine and poultry.
And so there is a...
as a result of the published material on grain sorghum feeding, there is this, and there are reprints available on this chapter that we have.
Now, we tried a few years ago, I'm going to mention this, although it resulted in no practical application, a few years ago, I was very much interested in...
how we could improve the survival of the poultry embryo from day old, from the time of setting of the egg, to 21 days when they hatch.
And so we developed a plastic shell.
It's in two pieces, and it's clear and has a snap on cover.
And so we got a mold made and had these made for us by one of the companies in Fort Worth, plastic companies.
And we tried to use this, we put the shell, take the egg out of the shell and put it into this plastic shell and then put it in the incubator to try to make it develop.
Well, we just don't know, and I suspected this might be the case, but we just don't know enough biology at the present time to take that all the way through
to 21 days.
This is what I'd like to do, would be to take it all the way through to 21 days.
Then we could check it for injections, the effects of different additives, feed additives, whether they were toxic or non-toxic, etc.
Just many, many uses could be made of this.
About all the value it was, or is at this time to us, or proved to be, we've discontinued any interest in it right this minute, but the youngsters all over the country used this plastic eggshell.
as a science project in their school work.
And they put these embryos in there and they can watch the blood island form on the germinal disc
Then they can watch the blood vessels form.
Then they can watch the heart form, and they can see the heart beating and pumping.
They see it's completely clear, and they can watch the heart pumping the blood out the arteries and back through the veins and so on.
So it's been used.
I've shipped those things all over the world, as a matter of fact, but particularly over the United States.

I had one extension told him in Ohio that every year he would order a couple hundred of those shells, if I had that many, he'd order them every year to distribute to the kids in Ohio for their science, those that were interested in eggs as a science project.
And so we've discontinued because we've gone just about as far as we can on this.
We're just going to have to learn more biology before we can take them all the way through.
But there's some hope that you might be able to do that someday.
Oh, I don't think in a doubt that we'll be able to do it someday.
I won't, but I won't live that long, but somebody will.
Yes, indeed.
Then we...
We did some work on clay feeding, bentonite and clay work, and we have gotten some definite responses from feeding of clay to these laying hens.
There's also been some reports since our first paper, there's been some reports from other areas for feeding it to broilers.
How they get any additional response
from the feed because it includes a little clay, I do not know.
And I will never have time to really determine one of the suspicions I have as to why.
I have a feeling that probably these clays are extremely fine particles, most of the clays.

And I have a feeling that the nutrients coat these clay particles and that gives a greater surface exposure to the villi on the lining of the digestive tract so that the absorption rate is perhaps higher.
I don't know that this is it, but I'd like to be able to test it.
And I got far enough to get a company that said they would make me clays of different glands.
granular sizes so I could do it.
I may get back to it in my retirement days and further test it, but that's as far as we've gone on that.
And then there's two other areas that I'd definitely like to mention that I think we've made some fairly original contributions.
One is that quite a number of years ago, we fed to these laying hens, we fed...
eggs.
We simply took the feed and then put in the equivalent of one egg per man per day.
Two eggs, three eggs, four eggs, seven eggs, and ten eggs per man per day.
And fed these hens for a full year.
on this to determine about this cholesterol thing that we hear so much about, particularly in the medical profession.
Well, we actually found that the higher the level of eggs we included, the better the performance of the birds and the lower the mortality.
I don't think there's any doubt that this is significant.
And then the... Can we step back to that a minute?
You say one egg per man per day.
Now, do you mean per chicken?
Yeah.
In other words, that hen consumed in her diet, she consumed the amount of egg that a man would consume...
in a day.
I wanted to feed these hens at different levels of consumption, of egg consumption.
So I fed them on equivalent to a man basis, you see.
In other words, this group of hens got no eggs added.
This one got the equivalent eggs added, equivalent to a man, an average man and woman, and the average size, consuming one egg per man per day.
And then two and so on, up to ten eggs per man, equivalent of a man would be eating ten eggs if he had got as much eggs as his hen was getting, don't you see?
So you would adjust for the body weight of the chicken.
A chicken of a certain size would get a certain portion of an egg.
Yes, yeah.
And in other words, the ratio was here so we could check to see what effect these eggs had, the cholesterol in the eggs.
There were whole eggs given to these birds.
And we also did some work and were asked to report it at several seminars on the relation of
calcium source and the particle size of the calcium, its relation to eggshell quality.
You see, the feeding of oyster shell, for example, supplementary shell, would it do any good in terms of improving shell quality?
And so we did, there were about three years' work in this area.
I think this made a real contribution.
Oh, we have also did quite an extensive amount of work
feeding of dwarf or many layers, the dwarf birds versus normal birds.
And we have showed that to get optimum performance from the dwarf birds, you have to feed a higher density diet.
Their capacity is lower, and thus you have to increase the concentration of the nutrients in the diet that they get.
And we were early in doing that.
